To terminate a C program, you can use the `exit()` function from the `stdlib.h` library. The `exit()` function takes an integer argument that represents the exit status of the program. Here's an example of how to use it:

```c
#include <stdio.h>
#include <stdlib.h>

int main() {
    printf("Hello, World!\n");

    // Terminate the program
    exit(0);

    // This line will not be executed
    printf("Program should have terminated by now.\n");

    return 0;
}
```

In this example, the `exit(0)` function call terminates the program with a status code of 0, indicating successful execution. The line after the `exit()` call will not be executed because the program has already terminated.

